1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:05,240
If you stay, I'll show you the easiest way 
to kick start your day trading journey,  

2
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:07,009
even if you're a total beginner!
 
So what is day trading. Well,  

3
00:00:07,009 --> 00:00:07,089
it’s when you buy and sell different 
instruments, such as stocks, currencies,  

4
00:00:07,089 --> 00:00:07,178
or crypto, within the same trading day. 
 
When you’re day trading, you closely monitor  

5
00:00:07,178 --> 00:00:07,269
market movements, you analyze charts, and use 
price action or technical indicators to find  

6
00:00:07,269 --> 00:00:07,320
potential trading opportunities. 
 
Market structure 

7
00:00:07,320 --> 00:00:11,360
Day trading starts with the market 
structure. You open a candlestick  

8
00:00:11,360 --> 00:00:17,560
chart, you zoom out, and start reading.
A successful day trader must learn to ride  

9
00:00:17,560 --> 00:00:24,360
market trends and figuring out who's running 
the show in the market, buyers or sellers. 
  

10
00:00:24,360 --> 00:00:28,400
This is the first big secret to 
successful day trading: finding  

11
00:00:28,400 --> 00:00:34,560
trades in the direction of the dominant trend.
An uptrend is like a staircase, with each new  

12
00:00:34,560 --> 00:00:39,200
high stepping above the previous one.
As long as the lows keep respecting  

13
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:46,560
the previous lows, the buyers remain in control.
When the price takes a dive below a previous low,  

14
00:00:46,560 --> 00:00:52,382
that's a shift in market structure – a sign 
that the sellers might be taking over.
  

15
00:00:52,382 --> 00:00:58,080
On the flip side, a downtrend is like a slide, 
with each new low slipping below the last. 

16
00:00:58,080 --> 00:01:03,800
The sellers keep the pressure on, as long 
as the highs can't reach the previous high. 

17
00:01:03,800 --> 00:01:09,840
But when the price finally breaks above a previous 
high, it's a sign that the buyers might take  

18
00:01:09,840 --> 00:01:17,880
control. Again, it’s shift in market structure.
 
Sometimes, the market takes a break from trending. 

19
00:01:17,880 --> 00:01:24,880
This is when the price gets stuck in a sideways 
range, bouncing between supply and demand. We call  

20
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:27,320
this a consolidation. 
 
 
Trend trading 

21
00:01:27,320 --> 00:01:31,360
Now, trend trading is the 
perfect strategy for beginners. 

22
00:01:31,360 --> 00:01:36,600
The simplicity of following the dominant 
trend is precisely what makes it so powerful,  

23
00:01:36,600 --> 00:01:40,320
especially for newbies.
 
If your market is trending,  

24
00:01:40,320 --> 00:01:46,200
day trading pullbacks is your best choice.  
 
If it’s a trading range day, you’ll enter at  

25
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:52,000
the extremes of the range, and stay out of 
the middle because it can be very choppy. 
  

26
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:56,760
Even safer is to trade ranges that 
align with the previous trend. 

27
00:01:56,760 --> 00:02:03,360
So if you spot a consolidation after a previous 
uptrend, it’s better to trade only the lower side  

28
00:02:03,360 --> 00:02:08,720
of the range, looking for “buy” signals only.
You’re still trend trading…but  

29
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:11,480
during range bound conditions.
 
 
Price action and candlesticks analysis 

30
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:18,080
In order to correctly read the market, you must 
rely on price action and candlesticks analysis. 

31
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:21,920
Learn to read market momentum 
using candlesticks…and you’ll  

32
00:02:21,920 --> 00:02:27,080
be one step ahead of most traders.
 
It’s simple. The body of the candlestick  

33
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:32,120
shows the opening and closing prices.
The wicks show the highest and lowest  

34
00:02:32,120 --> 00:02:37,280
prices reached during that period.
Bullish candlestick are those where the  

35
00:02:37,280 --> 00:02:43,560
closing price is higher than the opening price.
Bearish ones are those with the closing price  

36
00:02:43,560 --> 00:02:48,080
lower than the opening price.
 
During trending days, it's all  

37
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:53,520
about price momentum and follow-ups.
When the market is in a strong uptrend,  

38
00:02:53,520 --> 00:02:59,840
you'll see a series of bullish trend candles, 
with decent-sized bodies and high closing prices. 

39
00:03:00,800 --> 00:03:08,280
The bars slowly ascend, creating a parabolic curve 
that makes you wish you had entered earlier. 
  

40
00:03:08,280 --> 00:03:15,240
Any pullback attempts are short-lived, with 
narrow bearish bars having wicks at the bottom. 

41
00:03:15,240 --> 00:03:22,040
The key is to look for more bullish bars than 
bearish ones, both in quality and quantity. 

42
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:26,640
If you witness these conditions, and 
market structure confirms the trend,  

43
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:31,120
look for “buy” opportunities.
 
 
In a strong downtrend,  

44
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:37,480
you'll see consecutive bearish bars with 
average-sized bodies and wicks on top. 

45
00:03:37,480 --> 00:03:43,640
Bullish pullback bars are small and short-lived. 
 
The close of each candle is  

46
00:03:43,640 --> 00:03:48,560
lower than the previous one.
Again, you look to “sell” pullbacks  

47
00:03:48,560 --> 00:03:55,200
if the market structure confirms the trend.
 
 
Another way to identify trends is by monitoring  

48
00:03:55,200 --> 00:04:02,080
highs and lows of the individual candlesticks.
In an uptrend, each follow-up bullish bar should  

49
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:07,800
have a higher high, a higher low, and 
higher close than the previous one. 
  

50
00:04:07,800 --> 00:04:15,280
For downtrends, bearish bars should make 
lower lows, lower highs, and lower closes. 

51
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:21,160
Again, when the market is trending, pullbacks 
are your best choice. You want to align your  

52
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:28,160
trades with the prevailing market sentiment.
 
Range days are harder to day trade. Ranges are  

53
00:04:28,160 --> 00:04:32,440
essentially consolidation phases.
To read a price action range,  

54
00:04:32,440 --> 00:04:36,880
you first you analyze wicks.
Ranges are filled with wicks,  

55
00:04:36,880 --> 00:04:42,280
especially at the top and bottom of the range.
These wicks represent failed attempts by  

56
00:04:42,280 --> 00:04:46,560
buyers and sellers to push the 
price beyond the boundaries.
  

57
00:04:46,560 --> 00:04:51,560
You’ll also notice an alternation 
between bullish and bearish strength. 

58
00:04:51,560 --> 00:04:57,720
In a range, both sides are active, but 
there is no consistency or continuation. 

59
00:04:57,720 --> 00:05:04,760
Bullish and bearish bars are roughly equal in 
quantity, and any strength is short-lived.
  

60
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:09,600
You’ll also see many Doji candles 
and overlapping price action. 

61
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:14,680
Doji candles indicate indecisiveness. 
Overlapping bars, where the size of  

62
00:05:14,680 --> 00:05:20,640
the bars are similar or inside each 
other, also suggest sideways movement.
  

63
00:05:20,640 --> 00:05:26,640
When you day trade ranges, you always enter at 
the extremes of the range. Not in the middle. 

64
00:05:26,640 --> 00:05:32,240
Look to “buy” the lower channel of the range 
during uptrends, and “sell” the upper channel  

65
00:05:32,240 --> 00:05:35,280
of the range during downtrends.
 
Supply and demand 

66
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:40,800
Market structure and candlestick analysis 
go hand in hand with supply and demand. 

67
00:05:40,800 --> 00:05:45,520
You see, when you day trade, you don’t 
have the ability to influence the market. 

68
00:05:45,520 --> 00:05:51,600
It's the big players that really move the market.
They're the ones with the buying and selling power  

69
00:05:51,600 --> 00:05:57,960
to create imbalances in supply and demand.
 
Know this: the smart money never places their  

70
00:05:57,960 --> 00:06:03,720
full position at once. They break it into 
smaller pieces, to avoid pushing the price  

71
00:06:03,720 --> 00:06:07,920
away from their desired entry point.
And that's where supply and  

72
00:06:07,920 --> 00:06:11,880
demand zones come into play.
These are the areas where the  

73
00:06:11,880 --> 00:06:18,520
banks have initiated positions, causing 
sharp advances or declines in price.
  

74
00:06:18,520 --> 00:06:25,360
Demand zones are like magnets, attracting 
buyers and causing the price to bounce back up. 

75
00:06:25,360 --> 00:06:29,760
They form when banks place a 
large number of “buy” positions,  

76
00:06:29,760 --> 00:06:36,600
creating an imbalance that sends the price higher.
Supply zones are pushing the price back down,  

77
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:41,360
when banks unload a significant 
number of “sell” positions.
 
  

78
00:06:41,360 --> 00:06:46,240
So, how do you spot these zones. You 
look for clues in the price action. 

79
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:51,520
You want to find sharp rises and declines 
– the footprints of the smart money. 

80
00:06:51,520 --> 00:06:55,720
Look for big, bold candles 
with little to no wicks. 

81
00:06:55,720 --> 00:06:59,520
These are the signs that the big 
players are making their move.
  

82
00:07:00,120 --> 00:07:04,360
To find demand zones, look for a fast upward move. 

83
00:07:04,360 --> 00:07:10,040
Place a line at the high of the most recent 
red candle before the price increase,  

84
00:07:10,040 --> 00:07:17,280
and another at the most recent swing low. 
 
For supply zones, look for a sharp decline and  

85
00:07:17,280 --> 00:07:24,120
place your lines at the low of the most recent 
green candle and the most recent swing high. 
  

86
00:07:24,120 --> 00:07:29,520
In theory, when price revisits these 
areas, it has the potential to reverse.
  

87
00:07:30,280 --> 00:07:34,480
Now here's the catch – not 
all zones are created equal. 

88
00:07:34,480 --> 00:07:40,280
There are two golden rules you need to remember.
Recent zones are far more powerful than old ones. 

89
00:07:40,280 --> 00:07:45,520
The market is more likely to respond to 
zones that have been created recently.
  

90
00:07:45,520 --> 00:07:53,200
Second, supply and demand zones are one-time use 
only. Once the price hits a zone and reverses,  

91
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:59,440
it loses its power. The probability of another 
reversal at the same spot is much lower. 
 
 

92
00:08:00,680 --> 00:08:06,240
There are four main types of price 
structures that create supply/demand zones. 

93
00:08:06,240 --> 00:08:11,360
The "Rally-base-Rally" is a demand 
zone that forms during an uptrend. 

94
00:08:11,360 --> 00:08:17,840
It's like a pit stop for the price to catch its 
breath before continuing its upward momentum. 

95
00:08:17,840 --> 00:08:22,280
First, you'll see a rally, then a 
little consolidation (also known  

96
00:08:22,280 --> 00:08:29,720
as the base), and finally another rally. 
 
 
On the flip side, we have the "Drop-base-Drop",  

97
00:08:29,720 --> 00:08:33,840
which is a supply zone that 
forms during a downtrend. 

98
00:08:33,840 --> 00:08:38,720
You'll see a drop, then a little 
consolidation, and finally another  

99
00:08:38,720 --> 00:08:46,200
drop. This is also a continuation pattern.
 
The "Drop-base-Rally" forms a demand zone when  

100
00:08:46,200 --> 00:08:53,080
the market decides to switch from falling, to 
rising. You'll see a drop, a base, and then a  

101
00:08:53,080 --> 00:08:59,600
rally. This creates your demand zone.
 
We also have the "Rally-base-Drop",  

102
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:04,600
which forms a supply zone when the 
market decides to switch from rising,  

103
00:09:04,600 --> 00:09:13,200
to falling. You'll see a rally, a base, and then 
a drop. And this creates your supply zone.
 
  

104
00:09:13,200 --> 00:09:19,960
All these zones are like magnets for future price 
action. When the price revisits a demand zone,  

105
00:09:19,960 --> 00:09:24,720
it's likely to bounce back up 
and continue its upward trend. 

106
00:09:24,720 --> 00:09:32,280
When the price revisits a supply zone, it's likely 
to get rejected and continue its downward trend. 

107
00:09:32,280 --> 00:09:36,740
So when the price approaches these 
zones, look for opportunities!
  

108
00:09:36,740 --> 00:09:41,040
VSA
Volume Spread Analysis is the ultimate weapon in  

109
00:09:41,040 --> 00:09:48,320
day trading, the secret sauce that will help you 
understand imbalances between supply and demand. 

110
00:09:48,320 --> 00:09:55,080
V S A has 2 main components: spread and volume.
 
Spread is the difference between the  

111
00:09:55,080 --> 00:10:01,840
opening and closing price of a candlestick.
It's like the market's way of showing us how much  

112
00:10:01,840 --> 00:10:08,120
ground it covered during a specific time period.
A wide spread means there was a lot of  

113
00:10:08,120 --> 00:10:13,680
price movement, while a narrow 
spread indicates less activity.
  

114
00:10:13,680 --> 00:10:19,560
Volume shows the number of transactions 
that occurred during that same time period. 

115
00:10:19,560 --> 00:10:25,920
It's like the market's way of showing us how 
much effort was put into that price movement. 

116
00:10:25,920 --> 00:10:29,320
High volume means there 
was a lot of participation,  

117
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:37,280
while low volume suggests a lack of interest.
 
There are 2 main V S A concepts:  

118
00:10:37,280 --> 00:10:43,040
Sign of Strength and Sign of Weakness.
Sign of Strength is when the market is  

119
00:10:43,040 --> 00:10:49,440
showing you that the buyers are in control 
and demand is overpowering supply. This  

120
00:10:49,440 --> 00:10:55,480
imbalance causes the market to rise.
 
Sign of Weakness is when the market  

121
00:10:55,480 --> 00:11:01,680
is telling you that the sellers are in 
control and supply is overwhelming demand.  

122
00:11:01,680 --> 00:11:09,800
This imbalance leads to a market decline.
 
 
V S A goes hand in hand with the WYckoff method. 

123
00:11:09,800 --> 00:11:14,320
According to this theory, changes 
in market price are the result of  

124
00:11:14,320 --> 00:11:21,400
effort versus result, volume versus price.
If price action and volume are in sync,  

125
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:25,440
the trend is likely to continue.
But if there's a significant  

126
00:11:25,440 --> 00:11:32,080
difference between volume and price, the 
trend may be about to change direction.
  

127
00:11:32,080 --> 00:11:39,120
These are the top five Sign of Strength patterns.
First up, we have the "Down Thrust." This appears  

128
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:45,920
as a bullish pin bar or a Doji candle 
with ultra-high or above-average volume. 

129
00:11:45,920 --> 00:11:50,240
The spread is super low, 
but the volume is very high. 

130
00:11:50,240 --> 00:11:56,360
V S A tells you that low spread should mean 
low volume, but when there's a mismatch,  

131
00:11:56,360 --> 00:12:04,440
it's a sign that demand is overpowering supply, 
potentially causing price to rise in near future.
  

132
00:12:04,440 --> 00:12:11,200
Next, we have the "Selling Climax." This one 
shows up as a high-spread bearish candle with  

133
00:12:11,200 --> 00:12:18,200
a big downward rejection wick, accompanied 
by ultra-high or above-average volume. 

134
00:12:18,200 --> 00:12:23,840
This signals that the market could rise 
because there is more demand than supply.
 
  

135
00:12:23,840 --> 00:12:30,160
We also have "Bearish Effort lower than the 
Bearish Result." This pattern appears as a  

136
00:12:30,160 --> 00:12:37,840
high-spread bearish candle with a larger spread 
than the previous candle, but the volume is lower. 

137
00:12:37,840 --> 00:12:42,480
It's like the sellers are trying to 
push prices down, but they just can't  

138
00:12:42,480 --> 00:12:49,720
gain strength. This disagreement between price 
and volume could lead to a bullish breakout.
 
  

139
00:12:49,720 --> 00:12:55,800
On the flip side, we have "Bearish Effort 
higher than the Bearish Result." This one  

140
00:12:55,800 --> 00:13:01,040
shows up as a low-spread bearish candle 
with a smaller spread than the previous  

141
00:13:01,040 --> 00:13:06,720
candle, but the volume is higher.
It's like the sellers are pushing hard,  

142
00:13:06,720 --> 00:13:12,440
but the price don’t move much. This clash 
between volume and price could be a sign  

143
00:13:12,440 --> 00:13:18,880
that the buyers are about to take over.
 
We can also have the "No Supply Bar." This  

144
00:13:18,880 --> 00:13:25,800
pattern appears as a low-spread bearish candle 
with a downward wick and lower volume than the  

145
00:13:25,800 --> 00:13:32,240
previous two candles. It's like the sellers have 
just disappeared, leaving the buyers to run the  

146
00:13:32,240 --> 00:13:40,880
show. When supply dries up, prices tend to rise.
 
 
Sign of Weakness patterns are the market's way of  

147
00:13:40,880 --> 00:13:46,960
waving a red flag, warning you that the 
sellers might be ready to take control. 

148
00:13:46,960 --> 00:13:53,960
First, we have the "Up Thrust." This pattern 
appears as a bearish pin bar or doji candle with  

149
00:13:53,960 --> 00:14:01,200
ultra-high or above-average volume. The spread 
is super low, but the volume is going crazy. When  

150
00:14:01,200 --> 00:14:08,400
there's a mismatch between spread and volume, 
price has potential to fall in near future.
  

151
00:14:08,400 --> 00:14:14,920
Next, we have the "Buying Climax." This one 
shows up as a high-spread bullish candle with  

152
00:14:14,920 --> 00:14:21,600
a big upward rejection wick, paired with 
ultra-high or above-average volume. When  

153
00:14:21,600 --> 00:14:27,320
supply overpowers demand, it's time 
to watch out for a potential drop.
  

154
00:14:27,320 --> 00:14:32,880
Next we have "Bullish Effort lower than 
the Bullish Result." This pattern appears  

155
00:14:32,880 --> 00:14:38,600
as a high-spread bullish candle with a 
larger spread than the previous candle,  

156
00:14:38,600 --> 00:14:42,640
but here's the catch: the volume is lower.
If there's no effort, there shouldn't be  

157
00:14:42,640 --> 00:14:47,640
a result. This disagreement between 
price and volume could be a sign that  

158
00:14:47,640 --> 00:14:54,120
the market might decrease in the future.
 
On the other hand, we have "Bullish Effort  

159
00:14:54,120 --> 00:15:00,360
higher than the Bullish Result." This one 
shows up as a low-spread bullish candle with  

160
00:15:00,360 --> 00:15:05,320
a smaller spread than the previous 
candle, but the volume is higher. 

161
00:15:05,320 --> 00:15:11,480
When volume and price don't see eye to 
eye, price could fall in near future.
  

162
00:15:11,480 --> 00:15:17,600
We also have the "No Demand Bar." This 
pattern appears as a low-spread bullish  

163
00:15:17,600 --> 00:15:23,480
candle with an upward wick and lower 
volume than the previous two candles. 

164
00:15:23,480 --> 00:15:29,200
It's like the buyers have left the building, 
leaving the sellers to run the show. When  

165
00:15:29,200 --> 00:15:35,640
demand dries up, prices tend to fall.
Learn all these patterns because Volume  

166
00:15:35,640 --> 00:15:41,160
Spread Analysis is one of the most 
powerful day trading strategies. 
 
  

167
00:15:41,160 --> 00:15:44,960
VWAP
VWAP is one of the best day trading indicators. 

168
00:15:44,960 --> 00:15:49,640
VWAP is a dynamic indicator that 
updates throughout the trading day,  

169
00:15:49,640 --> 00:15:56,040
giving you a real-time view of where the price 
is trading in relation to its "fair value."
  

170
00:15:56,040 --> 00:16:02,760
VWAP is like a magnet for price action. It 
acts as a dynamic support or resistance level,  

171
00:16:02,760 --> 00:16:08,840
and price tends to gravitate towards it.
When a market is trading above VWAP,  

172
00:16:08,840 --> 00:16:16,120
buyers are in control, and when it's trading 
below it, the sellers running the show.
  

173
00:16:16,120 --> 00:16:22,560
VWAP can also help you find potential entry and 
exit points. When the price is trading above  

174
00:16:22,560 --> 00:16:29,040
VWAP and suddenly dips below it, it could 
be a sign that the buyers are losing steam  

175
00:16:29,040 --> 00:16:34,920
and it's time to consider selling. 
 
Or when the price is trading below VWAP  

176
00:16:34,920 --> 00:16:39,960
and suddenly pops above it, it could be a 
signal that the buyers are ready to take  

177
00:16:39,960 --> 00:16:46,480
charge and it might be the time to “buy”.
 
VWAP can also help you with the strength of  

178
00:16:46,480 --> 00:16:52,720
a trend. If price is consistently trading 
above VWAP and making higher highs,  

179
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:57,560
it's a sign of a healthy uptrend. 
 
Another strategy is to use VWAP in  

180
00:16:57,560 --> 00:17:04,080
combination with candlestick patterns. If price 
is trading above the main line and you see a  

181
00:17:04,080 --> 00:17:12,188
bullish candlestick pattern, like a candle with a 
long lower wick, it could be a sign to go long. 
  

182
00:17:12,188 --> 00:17:13,080
Pivot points
Pivot points  

183
00:17:13,080 --> 00:17:18,240
must be always present on your charts.
These levels are like a cheat sheet for  

184
00:17:18,240 --> 00:17:24,200
the market, telling you where the price is 
likely to find buying or selling pressure. 

185
00:17:24,200 --> 00:17:29,240
Pivot points can act as a magnet 
for price action, just like VWAP. 
  

186
00:17:29,240 --> 00:17:35,200
When a market is trading above the main pivot 
point, it's like the buyers are in control,  

187
00:17:35,200 --> 00:17:41,000
and when it's trading below the main pivot 
point, the sellers are running the show. 

188
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:45,800
But pivot points aren't just about the 
main level. The other pivot levels can  

189
00:17:45,800 --> 00:17:53,760
also provide potential entry and exit points. 
 
When price is trading near S1 or S2 level and  

190
00:17:53,760 --> 00:17:58,840
suddenly bounces higher, it could be a sign 
that the buyers are ready to take charge. 

191
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:06,800
When price is trading near R1 or 
R2 level and suddenly drops lower,  

192
00:18:06,800 --> 00:18:12,160
it could be a signal that the sellers 
are taking over and it's time to “sell”.
  

193
00:18:12,160 --> 00:18:19,040
A popular day trading strategy is to use these 
pivots as a guide for your entries and exits. 

194
00:18:19,040 --> 00:18:26,360
If you see price trading near a pivot and you spot 
a bullish candlestick pattern, or a VSA pattern,  

195
00:18:26,360 --> 00:18:29,080
it could be a sign to go long. 
 
Confluence of signals 

196
00:18:29,080 --> 00:18:34,360
Never enter into a day trading position 
without seeing confluence. This is  

197
00:18:34,360 --> 00:18:39,960
when multiple factors and signals come 
together at the same point in the market. 

198
00:18:39,960 --> 00:18:46,040
You want to find setups that have the same 
price signal from multiple methodologies.
  

199
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:52,600
Supply and demand zones, volume, pivots, 
all these factors will offer you signals. 

200
00:18:52,600 --> 00:18:57,320
When some of these tools start lining 
up at the same location on your chart,  

201
00:18:57,320 --> 00:19:02,440
you found a confluence area.
 
Let's say you spot a bullish V S  

202
00:19:02,440 --> 00:19:09,880
A pattern right near a daily pivot point. If 
the VWAP is also close, that’s a confluence.  

203
00:19:09,880 --> 00:19:15,400
A time to consider a buying position.
 
Or you find a supply zone that aligns  

204
00:19:15,400 --> 00:19:23,370
with a pivot point. If price momentum confirm 
that zone, you now have a “sell” opportunity.
  

205
00:19:23,370 --> 00:19:26,160
Day trading tips for beginners
After over 15 years of experience,  

206
00:19:26,160 --> 00:19:32,640
these are my best day trading tips for beginners.
First, use a small account or even a demo  

207
00:19:32,640 --> 00:19:37,680
account in your first 6 months, to 
practice and build your skills.
  

208
00:19:37,680 --> 00:19:43,880
Second, manage your risk like your life 
depends on it. Always use stop losses to  

209
00:19:43,880 --> 00:19:49,120
protect your downside, and don't 
let a single trade wipe you out.
  

210
00:19:49,120 --> 00:19:55,600
Also, losses are inevitable in day trading – 
you accept them and move on. And you don’t try  

211
00:19:55,600 --> 00:20:02,320
to get back your money after a losing trade. 
 
Also, keep your charts clean and simple. Less  

212
00:20:02,320 --> 00:20:08,080
is often more when it comes to day trading.
 
And accept the fact you won’t become an expert  

213
00:20:08,080 --> 00:20:13,400
day trader overnight. You need lots 
of market exposure. The more exposure  

214
00:20:13,400 --> 00:20:19,880
you have to different markets and setups, the 
better you'll become at pattern recognition.
  

215
00:20:19,880 --> 00:20:28,640
If this day trading guide helped you, make 
sure you don't miss out on our next video.

